The sample preparation procedure of milk was modified from a previous work [28]. A 15 mL aliquot of milk was added in a 50 mL centrifuge tube and centrifuged at 5000 rpm for 20 min to remove fat. Then, acetonitrile (15 mL) were added, vortexed for 1 min and centrifuged at 5000 rpm for 10 min to advocate protein precipitation. The supernatant was separated, transferred to an evaporating flask and evaporated at 60 °C. The residual was re-dissolved with 10.0 mL of ultrapure water. The analysis of cefazolin in spiked milk samples was also studied to evaluate the accuracy of the nano-optosensor. The recoveries of spiked milk were calculated from the following equation;

                              Recovery (%) = (Ctotal-Creal/Cspiked) ×100

                        where, Ctotal was the concentration of cefazolin after spiking a known amount of standard, Creal was the cefazolin concentration in a real sample and Cspiked was the concentration of standard spiked in a real sample.

To evaluate the selectivity of the nanocomposite GQDs-TiO2-MIP probe toward cefazolin, the developed nanoprobe was used to determine other antibiotics with similar chemical structures to cefazolin. These were cephalexin, cefatriaxone, cephradine, cefaperazone and ceftazidime. The results showed that the GQDs-TiO2-MIP probe provided high sensitivity toward cefazolin and low sensitivity toward the other antibiotics (
                        Fig. 6

                        ). This results implied that the MIP contained specific recognition cavities which were complementary in shape, size and functional group of analyte. Competitive binding was also investigated by determining cefazolin in the presence of different concentrations of cephalexin. Sensitivity was not significantly changed by the increasing concentration of cephalexin. These results indicated that the recognition cavities of the fabricated nanocomposite probe were specific for cefazolin.

The developed optosensor was applied to detect cefazolin in milk samples. Low concentrations of cefazolin (0.50 μg L−1) were found in the samples (Table 1
                        ). The accuracy of the method was determined by spiking milk with cefazolin standard solutions at 0.50, 1.0, 5.0 and 10.0 μg L−1. After pretreatment of spiked samples as described in Section 2.5, cefazolin was detected with the developed optosensor. Recoveries were achieved between 85.0 and 97.4 % with RSDs <5 %. The precision of the developed method was evaluated in terms of inter-day (n = 3) and intra-day (n = 6) performances. The RSDs for intra-day and inter-day precision were in the range of 1.1–4.4 and 1.5–4.8, respectively. The results confirmed that the precision of the optosensor was good. The analysis results obtained with the optosensor were compared with HPLC analysis. The results obtained using the developed optosensor and those from HPLC were in good agreement. The coefficient of determination (R2) was 0.995 with the slope and intercept of 0.9281 and 0.0014, respectively. HPLC chromatograms of milk samples spiked with cefazolin at various concentrations are shown in Fig. 8
                        . In addition, the sensitivity of the optosensor was higher than the sensitivity of the HPLC technique. This result confirmed that the optosensor using GQDs-TiO2-MIP probes could be used as a rapid, simple and accurate method for the detection of cefazolin in complex samples.
